<div class="page" id="page4">
      <p>
        <b>Sugar dissolving in water.</b> When sugar is dissolved in water, some H<sub>2</sub>O (water) molecules
        will bond with the molecules of sugar that are on the outer surface of the sugar crystals. 
        C<sub>12</sub>H<sub>22</sub>O<sub>11</sub> is the chemical formula for the molecules that make up both brown
        and white sugar. The oppositely-charged areas of the water and sugar molecules will attract each other. If the
        <a class="brm-link" href="../electric-force/index.html" target="_blank">electric forces</a>
        that cause the H<sub>2</sub>O-sugar molecule bondings are "strong" enough, the sugar molecule will be "freed"
        from its bonds with other sugar molecules and move about in the water. This is how sugar crystals dissolve in
        water. 
      </p>
